text:
#nofilteronlife day#2:
__
no, iâ€™m not moving. this box is actually a token of my worst nightmare. 
__
out of college i moved to ft. myers fl for a job. i honestly didnâ€™t have many friends and attempted to make them one night by going out downtown. 
__
i definitely drank a little too much but lost all my friends and didnâ€™t know the area well. so i did what anyone would do and tried to get a taxi home. 
__
i got into the backseat of a car that i thought in my inebriated state was an uber. 
__
they drove me to their house first and thatâ€™s when i realized something was wrong. i took my purse, got out of the car and threw a fit. they said they were bringing me home, so i started walking. i should have kept walking but they promised to bring me home. i should have known better. i donâ€™t know if i was drugged or what, but i knew what was going on and couldnâ€™t control much. 
__
the guy in a silver charger that iâ€™ll never forget took me to a home depot parking lot about two miles from my apartment. took me out of the car and started to assault me. 
__
i screamed and yelled and kicked and fought. the last think i remember is him yelling â€œfuck this!â€ and slamming his door shut and speeding away. 
__
i woke up across the street the next morning with my pants down to my knees. laying in the grass of a bank parking lot, i scrambled to collect myself. i had my purse and wallet, but no cell or keys. i walked barefoot back to my apartment two miles away. across a highway, and finally made it home. 
__
it was a sunday, and since i had no phone i had no way to call to ask for help. i didnâ€™t know any of my neighbors, so i found a large rock and broke through my window. 
__
i took off the t-shirt i was wearing, wrapped it around my hands and removed shards so i could crawl into my house. i cut my feet from all the glass lying on the floor. i donâ€™t remember the pain. i just felt numb. 
__
the first think i did was make a bath. in deep down logic i know thatâ€™s not what youâ€™re supposed to do, but iâ€™ve never felt so violated. i wanted to scrub my skin off. 
__
**post continued in comments**

text:
ğŸ—£ digital activism panel is on nov. 17 @ 12pm. in the wake of the #metoo movement, locally-based filmmakers and artists explore the implications this may have for women and trans folks belonging to communities of colour, black communities, and indigenous communities locally, and beyond. 
meet our panelist anique jordan!

self-taught artist, curator and writer anique jordan works in photography, sculpture, social practice and performance and has lectured on her artistic and community-engaged curatorial practice at harvard university, university of the west indies, mit, university of toronto and ucla. her art practice plays with the aesthetics found in traditional trinidadian carnival and the theory of hauntology challenging historical narratives and creating, what she calls, impossible images. #rpff18

text:
i yelled â€œme tooâ€.
the world went quiet and f*ck it felt so good to see you move.
to find your eyes in mine and say â€œoh baby girlâ€,
to cry and you cried too.
i need that,
i need to see that somewhere love breathes hope for me and you,
for all the faces turned to mine,
to find your hand reach mine and tears that made me blind,
entitled in the witnessing of others,
you found a way to stretch to all the brothers,
all our sisters that felt week,
all the words they cannot speak for fear of being found.
you sang the words, i cried,
so did the crowd.
you let your vulnerability shine rayes,
and mimicked in the mooring of the waves,
you start a ripple, still in early days
but now i am more proud of you,
for making space for me to shout â€œme tooâ€.

text: â€œalthough i never dug too deep into the #metoo movement on my own, i have heard about it from several people and sources thanks to social media. because of our generationâ€™s strong online presence, a movement like this is able to happen and grow locally and internationally, and take flight for a better future. if people werenâ€™t as connected or literate with the online world as they are now, itâ€™s scary to think of where women would be without this sanctuary of healing and hope thatâ€™s held within the metoo movement. with the rise of womenâ€™s empowerment, i hope one day women get the sought out justice they deserve. in the wise words of queen b, â€˜who runs the world? girls!â€™â€ - jazz jauregui, 2nd year music performance and education sciences major, aspiring music teacher and performer.

text: â€œ#metoo means #ustoo. this movement has created within us a sense of solidarity, love, and power. my girl squad found each other through using this hashtag on instagram - if it wasnâ€™t for instagram, i wouldnâ€™t have found such understanding and empathetic roommates who make me feel safe on a college campus. over instagram, we bonded over the meaning of consent. in the 21st century, people everywhere need to solidify the meaning of consent. i believe that consent is a 21st century literacy, and although finding each other through shared values might take us down into an echo chamber, we strongly believe that the #metoo isnâ€™t just a moment, itâ€™s the movement. and we need to be allies with each other and agree with each other to prevent the mistreatment of our roommates and our sisters.â€ - crystal xu, first year business economics major, proud chinese-american woman.

text: #metoo not only inspires women in the united states and at uci, but also encourages college women in korea. jo min-ki, a famous actor and a prominent drama professor in a provincial university, was accused of assaulting at least eight students from his class. those students posted the evidence to indicate that jo min-ki as a professor in university and an actor in korea had assaulted them. starting at school, more and more korean people began to focus on this movement because as a prominent professor in a university and a famous actor, who could imagine that jo min-ki had assaulted students who were the same age as his daughter? citizens have also been encouraged by the actions that eight students had done; since before the movement, it was hard for traditional korean women to tell their sexual harassment stories in social media. with the exposure on tv and other social media, women in korean told their sexual harassment stories that happened not only in school, but also in the workplace. because of the wide-spread information in social media, people in korean started to write letters to the university and government to accuse jo min-kiâ€™s behavior.  at last, jo min-ki had lost his job in the wake of accusations from those eight students and other korean people who would like to speak out for themselves. the #metoo movement includes all of us women, around the world, and although this photo gallery encompasses mostly women at uci, we wanted to expose the power the movement has had around the world.

text:
anything is possible in a pretty sweater and a clean house. but what if i had neither? iâ€™ve been thinking about that today.

the fact is, in addition to my career, iâ€™m also fortunate enough to have a charming little house of my own, complete with a closet full of clothing i can reach to for extra #empowerment or extra soothing.

lemme hit you with some tougher facts.

economic independence is a key indicator of whether a victim of domestic abuse makes it out. the #abused feel trapped. not just by the psychological dynamic their abusers create (called â€œtrauma bondingâ€) but also by the other hooks their abusers put in them... the hasty move-in, the whirlwind marriage (ahem), the baby he suddenly wants. these are an abuserâ€™s insurance policies, the things that assert financial control over how his prey lives.

according to @nnedv, #financialabuse occurs in 99% of #domesticviolence cases. it did in mine but the day after his sickest low, i remember sobbing desperately in my shower, then putting on this sweater. itâ€™s a stark black tunic, with pockets and a structured collar. anything is possible in a pretty sweater and a clean house... and i changed the door locks that day for the very last time. ğŸ’ªğŸ½ now, a year later, i want to help give that same power to other women, so iâ€™m going to be lending a hand (and a whole lotta energy) to @tubmanmn. they run a shelter and a service called harrietâ€™s closet, which provides women with the clothes they need before a job interview or court battle against their abusers. 
please consider donating to them on #givetothemaxday2018, which is this thursday. and start going through your closet for the pretty sweaters (and suits) you donâ€™t wear anymore, bâ€™c my friend and fellow #advocate @diymatthews and i are working on a donation event idea we suspect youâ€™ll want to be a part of. more on that prontissimo!.
.

text:
tonight a group of bold, strong, and empowered divinity school women gathered together to hold vigil; we lamented and prayed for the lost, forgotten, unnamed, and abused women of the bible. we honored jephthahâ€™s daughter, the unnamed concubine, hagar, and tamar. we lit candles for ourselves and the women in our own lives affected by violence, abuse, and neglect. we prayed for an end to oppressive systems, to slavery, and to assault â€¢ tonight a group of bold, strong, empowered divinity school women gathered together to hold vigil. we also gathered to love, to laugh, and to eat amazing home-cooked food. we enjoyed the company of the saints and fellowship with the holy spirit. i feel as if i can speak for everyone when i say that every emotion, from rage to joy, were felt in that space tonight. and i feel as if i can speak for everyone when i say that we serve a god who is constantly seeking justice and peace, working through everyday women like us â€¢ a prayer for #metoo by molly brewer:
â€œspirit of life and of love,
holy one that reaches wide to encompass all beings,
hold us to yourself in this moment.
we come to this place carrying so much in our hearts
around us we hear the laments of a broken world
torn by fire, storm and strife
crying, â€˜i too have suffered.
i too have been hurt and oppressed by power, by pain, by loss and by neglect.â€™
we open our ears and lift up the words of all who join in this sorrowful song: â€˜me tooâ€™
spirit, comfort us.
descend around us as cloud of peace and compassion,
abide with us in our mourning.
help us to gather ourselves,
to face each day with bravery, or equanimity, or even just to face it at all.
help make each movement lighter, less leaden.
give us the grace to once again give thanks,
and the strength to be kind to ourselves over and over.
one day, may our cries of shared sorrow give way to songs of joy,
may we sing, â€˜i too am healing my broken heart.
i too see the faces of justice and mercy.
i too am filled with light, love and compassion.
me, too.â€™â€ â€¢ #100daysofholiness

text:
call to action: the safepod challenge

speak up and force change! safety doesn't happen by accident!

please join safepod in the mission to end sexual violence by building a culture of consent by providing training to all students and staff on what a culture of consent looks like and on how to create safe spaces on campuses and in workplaces.

choose a business, organization or educational institution that you think should #makethecommitment

it is time we start asking for the promise and then holding them accountable.

post a status that says "safety doesn't happen by accident" and tag the institution of your choosing! let them know they have been nominated! share this post with 5 friends and ask them to do the same thing. use the hashtags #whenstrainingday #makethecommitment #cultureofconsent and tag or hashtag safepod - toronto and @safepod.toronto on instagram!

feel free to add as many hashtags as you would like!! if you own a business and you are unsure of what your first step should be! contact safepod or any local organization and ask how. get the conversation flowing. safepod can work with you to customize how your business can create a safe space as it is not a one size fits all solution.

bye bye rape culture

hello culture of consent

text: 194k might appear to be a law that protects sexual abuse survivors, but the reality of it is that people like jane doe are forcibly silenced. it protects the perpetrators, and gags those who want and deserve to share their stories. without the ability to come forward and speak, movements like #metoo couldnâ€™t have happened in the first place. to quote the megaphone petition: â€œthere is tremendous power in survivors owning their own stories without fear or stigma. it is incredibly disempowering for survivors who want to reclaim ownership of their narrative, to be told that they have no right to speak out about their own abuseâ€. take the power away from abusers. itâ€™s time we let survivors control the narrative. iâ€™m putting the petition to the supreme court of tasmania to allow survivors to waive their anonymity in my bio. please sign it, and spread the word. #letherspeak

text:
not 'fake it till you make it'. i saw this on @letstalktrauma one instagram post and it's true. you have to work through obstacles and challenges before you can make it. she's right. â–

i missed being authentic, really being proud of what i have achieved because i felt i tried to push my traumas to the side; i tried to push my eating habits to the side and anything else that made me feel unworthy. the result? more anxiety and more depression. so don't fake it till you make it.. face it till you make it. that's worth it. that is so much better.

text:
i skipped this because it felt too intimate & personal but here goes... day 10 of #bpsewvember is a letter to ourselves.

dear past me, 
it's okay to hurt, grieve, and be angry. bring those emotions in and process them. go to counseling, get on antidepressants. do what you have to do to heal, and don't let the negativity of others crush you. you can and will get through this. there are people out there who love you, don't lose sight of that. don't run. let this strengthen you instead of break you. you will be okay. when it's all too much, take a deep breath and try to find something worth living for. stay away from the pills. & if it's not too late, go to the police. press charges. openly talk about what you've been through. you will get closure and your healing will go a lot faster.

as ever,
kimber

p.s. and to tie this back to sewing, save yourself hundreds and start making your own underwear, you'll thank yourself later!

#metoo #metoomovement  #suicideprevention #suicideawareness #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #breakthestigma #nomeansno #sexualassault

this weekend i got to meet the face behind @skintosoul_ and bought a few amazing smelling soaps. i didn't tell her in person but aside from seeing her amazing stuff on ig, what sold me was her story. if you have some time go check the link in her bio.

ps: i also bought this amazing babes only shirt from another younge entrepreneur @shopmueve . i love that these two ladies have a similar passion as me, and are in the business of empowering other women.

text:
my love
it is bountiful
this opening has been practiced for generations 
the women that wandered here before
they too loved with a firey passion
a thrist quenched in transitory movement
a transition set in motion by the men who stole what was not theirs to take 
the goddess in her awakened from a young age
and since then
she has moved to expose herself as the warrior
the undeniable strength and fortitude that comes from a woman who demands to take her life into her own hands
a woman who molds her legacy with the flow of a rushing river
a legacy molded by the golden elixir coursing through the veins
of a goddess awakened
she is a force
see it in her patched up spirit 
my grandmother.
my mother.
my self. 
we are the trinity
we embody all that is love
we, the essence of life, bow down 
to the goddess awakened
our love
it is bountiful. #lovesteph

text:
thank you ğŸ™ 
all for watching my interview on @zoomtv , over 43 k people saw it ! i shared my experience on national tv which was a very difficult decision for me , thanks to the senior journalist #rudhrani and @soares_diandra i spoke out on the incidents i had faced while working in the #indian #filmindustry . the response and #love i got from people has been tremendous  and i am totally overwhelmed by it . this has boosted my belief in humanity again . 
i am glad that our country is finally ready to hear our women ,our side of the story, our #women need to #heard and #believed and not #shamed when we share our journeys and mishaps. some of us are the #first #generation of women who are choosing to work. 
i hope after watching this and hearing all the #metoo stories some important #laws are put into place and implemented which will guarantee the safety of our women and girls . women who go out to work after completing their education need their basic safety to be safeguarded and ensured no matter what profession . this is a very basic right of each and every individual backed by the #constitutionofindia . i hope the next generation of women wont have to face such horrific encounters and have to jeopardise their safety and respect for work. i also hope if men can take something away from this movement and understand the difference between #consent and no consent . there are too many miscommunications today amongst #men and #women . its time #respect is given to workplace #ethics and this behaviour strongly condemned . i will talk further on this topic as how #boundaries between the genders should be respected in every situation and not just work. the basic breakdown of #respect is what has caused this and its time its honoured again.
to watch the full interview 
please go on zoom tv https://youtu.be/chn4gz38l9k #metooindia #believewomen #nomeansno #genderequality #sexualharrasment #metoo

text:
i remember in my university days mentioning to my male friends that a man had followed me home or shouted at me on the street or grabbed me in a bar. i remember their shock and that look that meant "really? surely you are misinterpreting?" -
so many men have told me they had no idea, surely #metoo can't be the case for all women, otherwise they would have heard of these experiences before from the women in their lives?
-
well the time to claim ignorance is over, we need to tell the men in our lives about our experiences, big and small (when we feel safe and comfortable). when someone shouts at you on the street, tell the friends you are meeting. when someone grabs in a club, tell a bouncer or the police. when someone makes a comment or makes you feel uncomfortable, tell people. -
refuse to be silenced. refuse to let it slide unnoted. -
overwhelm men with tales of these experiences the way they overwhelm us.
-
-
-
-

â€œyou shouldnâ€™t have been out so late aloneâ€. â€œyou should have known wearing that would attract attentionâ€. â€œyou should have covered up â€“ what did you expectâ€? respect. to not be told what we â€œshouldâ€ have done.

these toxic phrases are all heard by women day after day - the result of which is a society that is desensitised to the issue of rape culture and young boys who develop the mentality that women are not deemed worthy of respect in the same way that they are. 
it has to stop.

text:
so, this is the week where dream's become reality!

nope, i'm not winning the lottery, not marrying daniel craig and not off to buy an audi r8!

this dream has been with me since i was a tiny girl.
the dream to write, to call myself an author and to publish a book. to inspire and empower other's with my words.

and after 18 month's its about to come true!

its not just happened! i've not just waved my magic wand and 72k words have appeared on my screen !

in truth it's taken time, heart ache, angst, tears and at times my sanity to make this come to fruition.

whatever your goal or dream, you can acheive them...... you just have to commit, do the graft and make it happen. 
no if, no but, no maybe!

just a i can and i will attitude!

start today on your goal........ where will you be in 18 month's time? 
you can achieve so much more than you ever thought possible. 
#memoir #itsnosecret #author #thrive #goals #survivor #metoo #justdoit @authors&co #somuchmorethanieverbelieved

text:
no one was there for me growing up. no one saved me from the hell i experienced as a kid. traumatized to the point of no recollection but at the same time i know without needing details. i raised my damn self. i forced myself to fight through and survive. i grew up in a scared, unsafe, lonely, isolated environment. i didnt know who i could trust or who i could turn to so i created my own reality and i've lived there ever since. i disassociate so regularly that i cannot tell reality from my reality. i cannot separate them no matter what. i still feel. i still sympathize for others. i'm not heartless or soulless. i refuse to become the monsters who robbed me of a normal childhood and upbringing.

text:
(part 2/2)
even in my teen and early adult life, abuse was an ongoing theme. my grandmother was so obsessive with her faith that it blinded her. she became the wedge that divided me from my father. as she planted seeds of hate into his mind. she called me names like the devils child, satan and child of a whore all because she did not like my mother. she was not sane, but everyone in the family left her unchecked including my father. 
i grew older and began to have relationships which would later echo the same abuse whether it was physicallyor mentally. those relationship always went longer than it needed to, despite the abuse. i been in many circumstances of rape, and sexual abuse of adult men and male friends or colleagues. 
so despite the many trauma is my life, i rise with fervor. what they thought and tried to do to break me, only harden me. i went from shutting my mouth afraid to speak to setting my path ablaze. 
the values and characteristics that those around me failed miserably at of integrity,  respect and honor are my greatest assets. 
this isn't meant for pity,  this is meant for strength.  we rise through the ashes of our trauma, i survive and so can you if you are in an abusive situation. those who abuse will chain you down to feed on you. if you know anyone in an abusive relationship,  abusive family. do not turn your cheek. seek help, guidance...there are many resources now than ever. simply put. there is no fucking excuse for abuse. .
now i have 2 young boys of my own, and super fucking supportive partner in all i do.  my own pain, life sufferings has molded and shaped me to become the healer i am, the mudang i am.

#repost from @enambelasffest
.
hai semua! 
sesuai yang dijanjikan, berikut adalah gambaran besar dari acara kita!
.
enam belas film festival adalah upaya kami untuk mengkampanyekan anti kekerasan berbasis gender & seksual selama kampanye global 16 days of activism atau yang biasa kita kenal sebagai kampanye 16 hari anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan #16haktp melalui film, diskusi & dialog.
.
tahun ini kali kedua kita menyelenggarakan enam belas film festival.
.
kami percaya bahwa pemulihan korban serta penanggulangan kekerasan seksual dapat kita lakukan jika seluruh masyarakat indonesia mampu menyadari bahwa kekerasan seksual harus kita akhiri.
.
untuk melanjutkan upaya dari perjuangan tersebut, kami pun kembali berkontribusi dengan mengadakan penayangan 16 film panjang, pendek, dan dokumenter karya anak bangsa yang mampu memicu mulainya pembicaraan mengenai kekerasan seksual. maraknya kasus demi kasus sepanjang tahun 2017-2018, membuat kita untuk semakin peduli dan turut andil dalam menghentikan kekerasan!.
.
tertarik datang? mau tau lebih lanjut film yang akan kita tayangin? tunggu postingan kami menuju hari pelaksanaan yaa!
.
#enambelasffest #gerakbersama #hapuskekerasanseksual #metoo #hearmetoo #nonprofit
#infoscreening
.

text:
some direct summary but detailed keypoints from the women's book by lyle mcdonlad that i promised you guys: 
women are not just little men.

me being a female and many of my female clients have made me realize there are women specific issues.

women face issues that men simple donâ€™t especially when it comes to fat loss.

we tend to gain weight and fat more easily along with endless other differences.

for example, mood changes, pms, strength and coordination changes.

the menstrual cycle alone introduced complications in womenâ€™s physiology that simply donâ€™t occur in men.

women also show differences in terms of how their mood, hunger,etc. change with almost no two women having the same exact pattern.

men are profoundly simple from a physiological standpoint.

there is a tremendously large amount of mistaken beliefs and information on the topic of fat loss and dieting especially for woman.

in most sports, at the elite level, womanâ€™s performance is about 8-10% below men.

however, in ultra-endurance running and cold water swimming, womenâ€™s performance is generally superior.

women also show better endurance and tolerate heat better than men.

while they lose fat more slowly, they also lose less muscle than men.

even now research on men is done at about a 4:1 ratio to that on women.

that's it for today...
.
check back in a while for more.
.
#femaleproblems
#womenfatloss #pms #menstrualcup #thewomanbook

text:
this past week saw a lot of astro weather "change events." the planet uranus, which represents "how we grow (or lose it) when the shit hits the fan," has backed out of the sign of taurus, a sign that wants the shit to never hit the fan, and into the sign of aries, a sign that will fight, fight, fight whatever hits the fan and will then rip down the goddam fan and start looking for the person who put the fan up in the first place so it can kick his ass. ğŸŒŸğŸŒŸğŸŒŸ
uranus was in aries for seven or eight years and entered taurus in may, just as the sun was also going into taurus. so now uranus is in the sign of aries, a fire sign if ever there was one. and as of this writing it is exactly square (at cross purposes with) the lunar nodes, which have just changed signs from leo/aquarius polarity into the cancer/capricorn polarity. it could help calm the waters, i hope and pray.
ğŸŒŸğŸŒŸğŸŒŸ
i'm not saying that uranus in aries caused the massive and massively tragic fires in california or the election fraud wars now underway around the usa or anything else for that matter. the stars incline, they do not compel, said ptolemy all those centuries ago and it is just as true today. but the camp fire looks like it was started by a massive electrical event on a high tension line and uranus rules electricity and aries is a fire sign. ğŸŒŸğŸŒŸğŸŒŸ
the other big change this past week was the planet jupiter, the biggest planet in our solar system and in astrology the planet that symbolizes how we grow when things go well, growth in general, optimism (jovial - jove was another name for jupiter) and jupiter left the sexy detective sign of scorpio, a year which saw the #metoo movement expand and expand, and is now in the sign of sagittarius, which is jupiter's favorite sign, the sign it "rules.â€ ğŸŒŸğŸŒŸğŸŒŸ
jupiter is sag is archetypal lucky. sigh. this could be really good, though i wouldn't blame anyone who is suffering from any of the myriad ills that plague us, like getting burned out of your home, from thinking that what i'm writing is fatuous bullshit,  but if i don't write what i believe to be true, what good am i?
ğŸŒŸğŸŒŸğŸŒŸ

text:
how the #metoo movement is changing hollywood. the map of power in hollywood is becoming increasingly pink. in the mecca of cinema, overwhelmed by a wave of sexual scandals, women are gaining positions as managers, directors and actresses, and the number of female stories is also increasing, as shown by some remakes like ghosbusters, with melissa mccarthy and kristen wiig, and oceanâ€™s 8 with cate blanchett, sandra bullock and rihanna, while the expendables 4  is being prepared, a new chapter of the saga launched by sylvester stallone this time played by a group of fierce fighters struggling with a treacherous misogynist sultan.
the tendency to adapt content to the times is not limited to a fairer redistribution of genre roles, but also takes into account the lgbt categories, as evidenced by disneyâ€™s willingness to present a sequel to the cartoon frozen in which elsa, her heroine, is a lesbian and does not hide having a girlfriend by her side. this real revolution started from the power list of the most sought-after management seats, so much so that several prominent executives have been replaced by women. .
.
.
.

text: #protectourgirlscampaign...silence is empty...unable to feel, dejected, undiscerning. fear, shock, and disappointment fills the void of speech. but in that silence we hear the pain of our inner being and begin to cultivate hope within- - -because in that silence you've built a wall between yourself and reality which no one can enter nor defile, nor desecrate. "i stood in the dining room of my aunt's house waiting for my cousin to appear from upstairs, excited about our day...for no reason at all besides the fact that we were kids with vivid imaginations...my uncle entered the house as my back was turned and grabbed me from behind groping my bottom, as i stood in shock. seconds seeming more like hours, and just like that - - -he stopped. he kept walking into the kitchen and suddenly turned and unleashed a penetrating gaze into my fearful and questioning eyes...and lifted his finger to his lips to quiet my thoughts...ssssshhh". and he walked away and i never spoke of it, but never forgot it. #silencehurts #speakup #speakout #shareyourstory #youarenotalone #ourchildren #ourresponsibility #endthesilence #youarenotalone #childsexualabuseawareness #metoo #pogc #dontbeafraid

you've probably woken up to the "me too" movement on social media or you'd open up your newspapers to a "they tried to bury us but they didn't know we were seeds", it's all just a mess of motivational words and battle statements flying by everyone's ears and eyes..and why? 
it's human rights. it's what governs you. it's what you stand for and stand by. 
we've pulled in mr. shehara herath, a gentleman well versed with human rights, to dedicate an hour's time of putting into place the regulations that sustain global movements.

1. learn the signs and symptoms of abuse 
2. if you witness it , donâ€™t ignore it 
3. be there to listen 
4. be available to offer your time and support 
5. know the number to shelters nearby
6. check in regularly 
7. be a resource
8. document every incident you have been a witness to 
9. get the word out , spread awareness 
10. use your power as a consumer to refuse to buy into any products or entertainment that glorifies abuse

text:
twitter has exploded with pleas for hillary clinton to reconsider whatever thoughts she might be having about another shot at the presidency after her former adviser suggested she would run as a liberal firebrand in 2020.

a wall street journal opinion piece co-authored by mark penn, clintonâ€™s adviser in 1995-2008, came out under a somewhat clickbaity headline: â€œhillary will run again.â€ the 2016 democratic presidential candidate herself never said she would or would not do that, but the authors â€“ penn and former manhattan borough president andrew stein â€“ believe that a â€œhillary 4.0â€ is on the way.
â€œget ready for hillary clinton 4.0. more than 30 years in the making, this new version of mrs clinton, when she runs for president in 2020, will come full circle â€“ back to the universal-health-care-promoting progressive firebrand of 1994,â€ they wrote in the op-ed published on sunday. penn and stein believe that clinton should lean further left, capitalizing on the #metoo movement, advocating universal healthcare and stricter gun laws.

all of that, along with her burning desire to avenge a â€œhumiliating loss at the hands of an amateur,â€ will allow her to â€œeasily capture the 2020 [democratic] nomination,â€ the piece argues.

while the op-ed is largely speculative, it comes just two days after the former secretary of state hinted that she just might be launching another bid. having said that she does not want to run, clinton paradoxically admitted that she â€œwould like to be presidentâ€ during a questions-and-answers session on friday.

the op-edâ€™s authors suggest that clinton wonâ€™t hurry to jump in the race at first, but will do so â€œdefinitely by the time the primaries are in full swing.â€
the prospects of clinton giving it another go, however, are not so thrilling even for those who have been dreaming of a democrat retaking the white house in 2020. some have already started panicking, with one commentator tweeting that a remake of the clinton-trump showdown will â€œsignify the end of humanity.â€

.

.

.

this is an evolution of men.
.
the world evolves for one reason...survival.
.
survival used to be based on fittest, strongest, fastest.
.
but the world has developed new means of safety and strength. because of this, men are being called, corrected, and commanded up into a new expression.
.
our ability to adapt and exceed is proven by history.
.
we may, however, be in the midst of the hardest transition manhood has faced right now.
.
the inner realm of men. the masculine emotional body, the spirits of men have and are becoming the focal point of the worldâ€™s needs.

our survival depends on our resilience and our resilience is a result of our willingness to look at that which we have denied within ourselves.
.
our pain, our darkness, our demons, our inability to communicate effectively, our lack of capacity for our own emotions, our personal spiritually  irresponsibility.
.
this is the problem...but there is a solution!!!

we have a new podcast where weâ€™ve just scratched the surface of some of the ways men are stuck and some of the ways men can live from their hearts and lead from their hearts!

text:
i have found out what has been causing almost all of my medical issues. i am a survivor of trauma, diagnosed with c/ptsd. which means i have a complex anxiety problem that affects my entire nervous system. i tried to "forget" my trauma. i pushed it down so far that it has blindsided me in many ways. it has caused many health issues and have found some issues are directly related to injuries i endured.... but i have been so in denial that i never connected the dots. i have withdrawn from friendships, became an alcoholic, lied, stole, cheated and in many ways was giving up on life. i've lost friends, hurt family and have slowly been killing myself. i've been beating myself up for so long that it's hard sometimes to get through a day. 
but i am. one day at a time. sometimes one second. i am speaking to others about what happened, getting professional help and gaining myself back little by little. i have my good days and days i cannot function. but there are good days. i have so much support around me, especially by my husband! i don't know where i'd be without him. i've opened up to my family about my trauma and little by little my memory is coming back. i can't remember everything because i pushed it down so much. which in a way i thought was good... but those times when i get anxiety out of nowhere i wonder did something like this happen to me before or a smell or a taste. it can be very real and scary.

this isn't about my weaknesses though... this is about my strength! 
i'm a survivor. period. i'm fucking strong as hell. my story is about not me being physically, emotionally, mentally and sexually abused. it's about me always being strong through it all to have gotten away. when i picture my story i want to remember me challenging this monster. fighting back. not giving up. and getting away. that sweet freedom. i want to feel that freedom. freedom. i am no longer a victim of yours. i'm the woman who was strong enough to get away from you! 
this post is not for you to treat me differently, to feel sorry, to understand. this post is for the women out there who need support. we need each other. this post is for me, breaking the silence. this is my #metoo

text:
caption-
what am i? 
you must be thinking that i framed the question in the wrong way because i am a human being, i should say who am i.
but seriously, ask yourself, do you treat me or atleast consider me like a fellow human being? do you?
what am i?
a piece of mockery for you because of my, wait, how do you say it, "dirty little secret" right?
what am i?
just a creature who brought up shame on this filthy little society of yours because of my identity. 
what am i?
that little faggot who is a stinking stain on this so clearly, pious community of yours. 
what am i?
no. not anymore. ask who am i?
i am as much a human being as you are. i am a gay. i am a homosexual. i am a bisexual. i am a transgender. i am a lesbian. i am so much more.
but, that is my identity. and clearly, you do not have any right to question my identity. 
who made this rule that boys should only love girls and girls should only love boys? oh! look, some of those religious ones say that it was the god. now, was it?
were you there with the goddess/god when she/he said so?
no, right?
from what i could remember, a human being can love another human being and what is the gender of anybody's partner shouldn't be any of your business. 
if you have so much time on yourself, the world is suffering through some major problems like terrorism, illiteracy, hunger, poverty, human trafficking, and so many others. so please divert your attention to some real problems instead of targeting love. @thewashroomstories @poets @nikita_gill

text:
[goddesses with grenades]
iâ€™m carrying a jute bag
full of fallen stars
i collected while digging my grave

they stabbed me with the knife of culture
sharpened with self-proclaimed morality

they clasped my tongue
for i dared to unapologetically chant
the spells of feminism
in a world haunted by men

my worth was decided 
by the size of my breasts
and the curve of my hip

i refused to wrap the packet of stayfree in black
and argued about staying free during menstruation
but was greeted with 
shhs and cold gazes

i felt a sudden titanic shift in my mind
and wanted to ask
why is it okay to talk about wars
about many dying in punjab train accident
about honour killing
about girls being raped
about brides being burned for dowry...
but not about a biological phenomenon like menstruation

they donâ€™t let me enter temples and kitchens when i bleed
and then question me why iâ€™m an atheist

they didnâ€™t bother to ask for my consent
before their dirty hands toured my body like a badly planned itinerary
and now they shame me for growing spikes all over my body

iâ€™m not the girl with a pearl earring
or the girl with the most beautiful smile

donâ€™t you dare sell me a magical fairness potion
when the world has been so unfair 
donâ€™t you dare sell me that serum for long and shiny hair
because iâ€™m a witch with anger braided in every strand of my hair

fuck you
iâ€™m going to claim whatâ€™s mine
iâ€™m going to claim what has always been mine

iâ€™m a goddess with a grenade
-prachi agrawal

text:
my boobs are not the problem 
in the last few weeks i've gotten lots of comments on my clothing, because it is at times "too revealing". i was told to change my profilepicture "[...]because not everybody has to know that you have [boobs]". yeah right, i guess i should change it then because people might find out that i have boobs - which are very rare for women to have- and which are of course a bad thing to have and therefor should be kept a secret. 
women are told to cover their bodies. not too much because that is considered prude. but not to little because then they are considered "sluts".
it is not right to judge and label women based on their outer appearence. an outifit does not determine who you are. and especially should not determine whether you should be treated with respect or disrespect. 
regardless of what i wear, i am worthy and to be treated with respect.
women are constantly told how to dress and that whatever they wear determines how they are going to be treated. hence society set standarts on what to wear.
if you wanna be raped (what an oxymoron itself) wear short skirts, 
if you want to be desirable wear something that is a little revealing and a little make-up,...
this really vague, sexist dresscode disproporitonately targets girls with the mentality that their bodies are sexual objects.
ignoring sexism is like telling harrassers they may act with impunity. 
women should have the same rights and freedom like men.
saying things like "thats just how it is. you have to be careful with what you wear, because men will be men and they will comment or harrass" is giving the oppressed or harrassed a wrong sense of guilt.this is called victimblaming. it teaches that it is acceptable to disrespect women if they choose to show their skin. women are held accountable for the actions of men. and that is wrong. this sort of mentality paves the way for sexual harrassment, sexual assault .

#feminism #everydaysexism #mybodymychoice #freethenipple #smashthepatriarchy #fucksexism #metoo #empoweredwomenempowerwomen #freedom #liberation #slutshaming #victimblaming #rapeculture

text:
a word from our director/choreographer, corrine bates, about 9 to 5, the musical: 
the year is 1979 and the workplace is not so kind to women, especially at consolidated industries, where our three leading ladies -  doralee, judy and violet, all work. their pompous, sexist, and domineering boss, franklin hart, demoralizes each of them in distinct ways. this intolerable work environment ultimately allows these three very different personalities to come together and stand up for what they deserve. the way hart treats these women, as well as all of the women in his office is horrifying, demeaning and completely unacceptable. we know this today. but this wasnâ€™t always a common knowledge and belief. the lines hart delivers are cringe-worthy and jaw-dropping, and for that reason we have come a long way, but we still have a long way to go. the themes in 9 to 5 are as relevant as ever. the #metoo, #timesup and #heforshe hashtags are all extremely important in our current year and remind us that there is still a lot of work to be done. the wonderful thing about 9 to 5 is that these women and men are not victims. the musical does an amazing job of showcasing that kindness, compassion and respect will always create a successful and positive environment and that you can absolutely accomplish anything you set your mind to. dolly partonâ€™s music and lyrics are exciting, catchy and truthful: â€œa better day is on the way, only you can change it.â€ .
.
11/16 @ 8:00pm
11/17 @ 2:00pm
11/18 @ 2:00pm
.
.

text:
this book is bleak. it has some a slightly  funny tone at times to help the reader digest its bleakness. i think that as women we are all aware (painfully aware) of the risk and the prevalence of sexual assault and rape that exist in our world but seeing the numbers (even if only centered on the us) is quite difficult. the book discusses every aspect of the culture that surrounds rapes, the myths we perpetuate, the treatment of the cases by the police and by media, the way we talk (or don't) talk about it. in the year of the #metoo movement and after cosby's sentence and weinstein's arrest, some of the most hopeful parts of this book feel more relevant. there's still a long way to go but maybe we are on the right path.

it's obvious that this is not a book you enjoy but i think it's a necessary one, a book that shows us a reality we might not be fully aware of.

do you read books on topics that you find difficult?

a year ago, alianza nacional de campesinas made a public statement of support on behalf of the individuals in the entertainment industry, who spoke out about workplace sexual violence. we were all inspired and empowered by tarana burke's me too movement - #metoo. since then, we have had the great honor of joining with women in the entertainment industry and other professions to say #timesup on this pervasive problem. we have also committed to working together to make workplaces, and all places, safer for everyone. watch the full video where we reaffirm this pledge here: https://youtu.be/t27h2iaxzf0

to learn more about #timesup and its legal defense fund for survivors of sexual assault in the workplace, please visit www.timesupnow.com.

to learn more about alianza and to support our work, go to www.campesinasunite.org. ---

text:
iâ€™ve recently realized that showers have become painful, again.
 my mind wanders on and on while my skin is getting bright red from the hot water, and i donâ€™t notice until well after the pain has settled in.
not too long ago, my ptsd got bad. quite a bit of hair had fallen out from stress and i had red marks on my skin from nervous clawing/scratchingâ€” which i hadnâ€™t done in years.
seeing the shadow of my naked body was just as painful as the hot water.
from april to august things were pretty much a mental hurricane. now looking at scattered storms.
most days are really good, sometimes with moments of pain. some days are just bad. iâ€™m constantly fighting these demons.
with that, iâ€™ve also noticed i call bullshit out more than before. iâ€™m taking care of myself and iâ€™m really happy about that.

text:
we're thrilled to welcome to our community local psychotherapist emily swanson.

emilyâ€™s work is trauma-informed and focuses on helping people find true belonging within themselves and the larger community. she is passionate about helping people move through pain and hardship to a place of inner clarity, strength, and joy. 
on wednesday evening, emily will be hosting a gathering at the indie alley that invites women to speak our experiences of the recent metoo movement, supreme court hearings and the historical wave of women joining congress. there is so much there to discuss, of how women are moving from pain to power.

come and speak your experience and combine your voice and strength with that of other women.

we'd love you to join us for this evening. you can register on our website as spaces are limited.

#metoo #postkavanaugh #trauma #therapy #gathering #womensgroups #womensstrength #womensupportingwomen

text:
free yourself from sexual trauma  #metooâ£
â£
in high school a group of boys were at my house. they were my sisters boyfriends friends. one of them aggressively threw himself on me repeatedly saying â€˜show me your cuntâ€™ as he grabbed me and tried to pull my pants off. i still cringe when i hear that word. i tried with all of my strength to push him off, with tears streaming down my face. the other 4 sat, laughed and did absolutely nothing to help.â£
â£
when traumatic experiences happens we naturally go into a natural stress response mode.. fight, flight or freeze. â£
â£
i knew what it was to fight and though i would be a â€˜fighterâ€™ regardless of what situation i found myself in.â£
â£
but something happened earlier this year that proved me wrong. a man walked by me, out of nowhere and literally grabbed my pussy. a lot of comedians have made jokes about this. i must admit, i found some of them funny, not at all regarding harassing women but just trying to wrap my head around the notion of â€˜grabbingâ€™ a pussy. but sadly, i found out itâ€™s a thing. it was so shocking i literally froze as he walked away. time stopped. i was paralysed in a combination of fear, disgust and rage.â£
â£
i kept replaying the scenario in by head wishing that i had snapped out of it sooner so i could have punched him in the face or scratched his eye balls out. â£
â£
if i saw it coming i may have run, if i felt safer i may have fought but i froze as the majority of women do when they are attacked, abused or rapped.â£
â£
the beneficial thing with â€˜fightâ€™ or â€˜flightâ€™ is that the physical movement of these actions helps to complete the stress cycles and free some of the trauma and the heavy emotions from your body. â£
â£
with the â€˜freezeâ€™ response the stress and energy from the event freezes within you too. becoming stagnant and leading to disempowering states in the body, body shame, sexual shame, pain, discomfort and even disease. unfortunately it can attract the same situations happening again. â£
â£
this is why you see animals in the wild heal after traumatic experiences by shaking their bodies profusely to release the stress from their bodies, returning them back to wholeness. â£

text_retweet:
ğŸ’œğŸ’œğŸ’œğŸ’œğŸ’œ #be_youagain #repost @whywomendontleave with @make_repost
ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
sometimes you go through things in your life that are awful. hell on earth.  some things are not okay. sometimes you get dealt a really bad hand. forcing yourself to be "positive" and see the bright side of a horrible event isn't necessarily the right way to handle things.  when i was diagnosed with breast cancer,  everyone in my life kept shoving rays of sunshine down my throat. "stay strong" and "fight like a girl"  everyone deals with trauma differently. i was just trying to get through each moment. the year of 2016 was pure hell for me. i was actually kicked out of a breast cancer support group because i was not "positive enough " of course i was going through chemotherapy and having an allergic reaction to the treatment but no one would listen to me. i was just accused of not being "positive enough "  there's some similarities between dealing with domestic abuse and cancer. these are two topics that make people very uncomfortable.  so well meaning people, and others want you to be strong and just move on. but sometimes that's because it's what they need, not what you need. it's okay to say "wow what happened to you was horrible" that's validation and we all should have the freedom to feel whatever emotions we need to.  that's not the same as behaving however you want. feelings and actions are two very different things. feelings aren't good or bad,  it's what you do with them. start where you are. i have been dealt some really lousy cards, but that doesn't mean i have to give up. i feel, i process and i keep moving forward.  that's how you survive. you don't quit.

text: thanks so much to all of the people who have messaged me and commented in regards to my â€˜ 1 in 20 children have been sexually abusedâ€™ blog post . i never for one minute wrote the blog for sympathy or anyone's sorrows even though i understand they come from a meaningful place and in some ways appreciate it more than i thought i would . instead, i wanted to raise as much awareness as possible as speaking about such a taboo subject is necessary. i can not believe how many people have messaged me in regards to their childhood experiences even though they haven't told many people, so for that i am grateful that you feel you can open up to me. the next blog post will be up on monday and again thank you for sharing this post as it is raising awareness even more. i am going to end it there because i am waffling now. goodnight all. lots of love, lauren x #metoo #metoomovement

text:
unpopular opinion of the day: ğŸ‘‰ it's ok to distance yourself from a toxic parent.
.
many times when people find out someone they care about is in an abusive relationship, their first reaction is to encourage the person to leave the abuser.
.
but i've noticed that whenever the person is being abused by a parent, people tend to advise them against ending contact. they say things like "he's still your father", "you only get one mom", "she carried you for nine months", and other things that make the abused person feel guilty.
.
it is my opinion that nobody is obligated to let someone subject them to a lifetime of abuse...even if it's their mom or dad. .
.
